node.text: International astronauts Akihiko Hoshide and Thomas Pesquet wrapped up their spacewalk at 3:09 p.m. EDT today after preparing the station for its next Roll-Out Solar Array.

node.title: International Astronauts Complete Power System Mods Spacewalk

node.text: NASA astronaut Shane Kimbrough (@astro_kimbrough) marks the 20th anniversary of the September 11 terrorist attacks with remarks from the International Space Station. “We will never forget,” says Kimbrough.

node.title: Recognizing the 9/11 Anniversary from Space Station

node.text: Russian cosmonauts Oleg Novitskiy and Pyotr Dubrov of Roscosmos concluded their spacewalk today at 6:16 p.m. EDT after 7 hours and 25 minutes. It was the second of up to 11 spacewalks to prepare the new Nauka multipurpose laboratory module for operations in space.

node.title: Cosmonauts Wrap Up Second Spacewalk to Set Up Science Module

node.text: The SpaceX Cargo Dragon arrived at the station 30 minutes early on Monday docking to the Harmony module's forward port at 10:30 a.m. EDT. Some of the new science experiments will explore radioactivity's affects on bone tissue, study astronaut vision issues, demonstrate robotic crew support, and ways to genetically engineer plants in space.

node.title: Cargo Dragon Delivers New Science and Supplies

node.text:
The astronauts aboard the International Space Station are ready for a big shipment of science experiments and supplies. From seeds to a robotic arm, @astro.megan and @astro_kimbrough will soon welcome research that launched early this morning aboard SpaceX’s 23rd commercial resupply mission to station.
 
#science #space #astronaut #ISS #SpaceStation #research #spacex

node.text: The Cargo Dragon spacecraft successfully launched on the SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket on Sunday at 3:14 a.m. EDT from NASA’s Kennedy Space Center in Florida. It will deliver more than 4,800 pounds of research, crew supplies and hardware to the International Space Station when docks on Monday at about 11 a.m.

node.title: Cargo Dragon Launches for Monday Docking to Station

node.text:
Experiments aboard the 23rd SpaceX Commercial Resupply Mission to the International Space Station include an investigation of protecting bone health with botanical byproducts, testing a way to monitor crew eye health, demonstrating improved dexterity of robots, exposing materials to the harsh environment of space, mitigating stress in plants, and more.

#space #science #research #spacestation #robotics #iss #nasa

node.title: Bone, plant and materials studies are ready for lift off!

node.text: Experiments that demonstrate 3D printing with dust, use engineered tissue to study muscle loss, and analyze growth of slime mold, along with other scientific studies and supplies, are headed to the International Space Station on Northrop Grumman’s 16th commercial resupply services mission (NG CRS-16). Launch of the Cygnus spacecraft is targeted for August 10 from NASA’s Wallops Flight Facility in Virginia.

node.title: 3D Printing, Muscle Cells, and Mold Experiments Launching to Space Station

node.text:
Key portions of the International Space Station are pictured from a window on Russia's newest addition to the orbiting lab, the Nauka Multipurpose Laboratory Module. From left to right are Japan's Kibo laboratory module with its attached Exposed Facility where a variety of experiments are placed in the vacuum of space, including: the Japanese robotic arm attached to Kibo; the Leonardo Multipurpose Logistics Module attached to the Tranquility module; and the seven-windowed cupola and the Bigelow Expandable Module, or BEAM, attached to Tranquility.

From front to back, Russia's Soyuz MS-18 spacecraft docked to the Rassvet module and the Nauka multipurpose laboratory module attached to the Zvezda module. The International Space Station was orbiting 264 miles above eastern Europe in this night time photograph that also highlights the Earth's airglow and the Milky Way.

node.text:
Astronaut Akihiko Hoshide checks out a pair of Astrobee robotic free-flyers inside the Kibo laboratory module on Aug. 26, 2021. Today, he configured the toaster-sized Astrobee robotic free-flyers to perform maneuvers using programs written by ground-based students from Japan and the United States. The event is designed to inspire the next generation of scientists and engineers to improve space-based and Earth-bound technologies.

node.text:
With the plans for Russian spaceflight participants to visit the space station as part of the Soyuz MS-19 crew in October 2021, NASA astronaut Mark Vande Hei and Roscosmos cosmonaut Pyotr Dubrov will remain aboard the station until March 2022. Upon return to Earth, Vande Hei will hold the record for longest single spaceflight for an American.

A potential benefit to this extension is NASA gaining deeper insight into how the human body adapts to life in microgravity for longer periods of time. This research helps prepare for Artemis missions to the Moon and eventually long-duration missions to Mars, as well as provides critical opportunities for additional research to be conducted aboard the station that can benefit life on Earth.

node.text:
The Genes in Space-8 study is shining on the space station. Or more accurately, fluorescing!

The study tests a Fluorescence Viewer measuring gene expression in space, which could improve medication delivery on future space missions. In the tubes a fluorescent dye binds to double-stranded DNA. Raising the temperature melts the strands apart and abolishes the fluorescence. Lowering temperature reverses that effect. (Sped up 1000x) 

Credit: Genes in Space

#science #dna #research #space #spacestation #iss #nasa

node.text: Russian cosmonauts Oleg Novitskiy and Pyotr Dubrov of Roscosmos concluded their spacewalk today at 6:16 p.m. EDT after 7 hours and 25 minutes. It was the second of up to 11 spacewalks to prepare the new Nauka multipurpose laboratory module for operations in space.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by International Space Station on September 08, 2021 tagging @roscosmosofficial, and @novitskiy_iss.

node.text:
(Pics 1 and 2) Russian spacewalkers Oleg Novitskiy and Pyotr Dubrov, pictured here on Sept. 3, will exit the station’s Poisk airlock on Thursday at 11 a.m. EDT to continue outfitting the Nauka multipurpose laboratory module for science operations live on NASA TV (link in profile). In pics 3 and 4, cosmonaut Pyotr Dubrov works to configure Nauka on Sept. 3. In pic 5, the Nauka module is pictured as the station orbited into a sunset above the southern Indian Ocean.

node.text:
Cosmonauts (from left) Pyotr Dubrov and Oleg Novitskiy will exit the space station on Friday at 10:35 a.m. EDT for a spacewalk to configure a new Russian science module for operations. The duo is seen here preparing their Orlan spacesuits for a previous spacewalk that took place in June.
